ies develop in early childhood","Rh positive individuals produce anti-D antibodies naturally"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of D antigen on red blood cells defines Rh negative status\u003C/strong\u003E. The D antigen is the most immunogenic of the Rh system antigens and is responsible for most clinically significant reactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERh antigens are carbohydrate molecules\u003C/strong\u003E - Rh antigens are proteins that span the red blood cell membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe d antigen is dominant over the D antigen\u003C/strong\u003E - There is no actual d antigen, only the presence or absence of D antigen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERh antibodies develop in early childhood\u003C/strong\u003E - Rh antibodies only develop after exposure to foreign Rh antigens, which can occur at any time\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERh positive individuals produce anti-D antibodies naturally\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike ABO antibodies, anti-D antibodies only develop after exposure through transfusion or pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the Rh system is crucial for preventing haemolytic disease of the newborn and ensuring safe blood transfusions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Rh blood group system consists of multiple antigens, with D being the most immunogenic and clinically significant.","Rh negative individuals lack the D antigen on their red blood cells.","Unlike ABO antibodies, anti-D antibodies only develop after exposure through transfusion or pregnancy."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of 